Thanks for sharing this vision! I see the core insight: moving the composition logic into the identifiers themselves, while keeping the container simple. Let me propose a redesign:

```javascript
class Sigil {
  constructor(name) {
    // Every Sigil has at least an implementation point and a resolution point
    this.impl = Symbol(`${name}:impl`);
    this.resolve = Symbol(`${name}:resolve`);
  }

  // Core factory method - subclasses define how their dependencies compose
  provider(dependencies, factory) {
    return {
      symbol: this.impl,
      dependencies,
      factory
    };
  }

  // The resolution chain - how this Sigil appears to dependents
  resolver() {
    return {
      symbol: this.resolve,
      dependencies: [this.impl],
      factory: (impl) => impl
    };
  }
}

class Singleton extends Sigil {
  resolver() {
    return {
      symbol: this.resolve,
      dependencies: [this.impl],
      factory: (impls) => {
        if (impls.length !== 1) {
          throw new Error(`Expected exactly one implementation for ${this.name}`);
        }
        return impls[0];
      }
    };
  }
}

class Composite extends Sigil {
  constructor(name) {
    super(name);
    // Additional extension points for decorators and aggregation
    this.decorate = Symbol(`${name}:decorate`);
    this.aggregate = Symbol(`${name}:aggregate`);
  }

  decorator(dependencies, factory) {
    return {
      symbol: this.decorate,
      dependencies,
      factory
    };
  }

  aggregator(dependencies, factory) {
    return {
      symbol: this.aggregate,
      dependencies,
      factory
    };
  }

  // The resolution chain becomes impl -> aggregate -> decorate -> resolve
  resolver() {
    return {
      symbol: this.resolve,
      dependencies: [this.impl, this.aggregate, this.decorate],
      factory: (impls, aggregator, decorators) => {
        const aggregated = aggregator(impls);
        return decorators.reduce((fn, decorate) => decorate(fn), aggregated);
      }
    };
  }
}

// The container becomes much simpler - it just manages dependency resolution
class Container {
  constructor() {
    this.providers = new Map();
  }

  provide(symbol, provider) {
    if (!this.providers.has(symbol)) {
      this.providers.set(symbol, []);
    }
    this.providers.get(symbol).push(provider);
  }

  resolve(symbol) {
    const providers = this.providers.get(symbol) || [];
    if (providers.length === 0) {
      throw new Error(`No providers for ${symbol.description}`);
    }
    return providers.map(p => p()).flat();
  }

  install(component) {
    this.provide(component.symbol, () => {
      const deps = component.dependencies.map(dep => this.resolve(dep));
      return component.factory(...deps);
    });
  }
}

// Usage example:
const log = new Singleton('log');
const converse = new Composite('converse');

const container = new Container();

// Install the resolver chains
container.install(log.resolver());
container.install(converse.resolver());

// Install components
container.install(log.provider([], () => console.log));
container.install(converse.provider([log.resolve], logger => msg => {
  logger(msg);
  return "Hello!";
}));
container.install(converse.decorator([log.resolve], logger => fn => (...args) => {
  logger("Calling function");
  return fn(...args);
}));
container.install(converse.aggregator([], () => impls => 
  msgs => impls.map(impl => impl(msgs)).join(" | ")
));

// Use it
const converseFn = container.resolve(converse.resolve)[0];
converseFn("Hi there!");
```

Key points in this design:

1. Sigils own their composition logic but not their state
2. Each Sigil defines its resolution chain through the `resolver()` method
3. The container just follows these chains, agnostic to what they mean
4. Extension points are explicit Symbols, making the flow clear
5. The container API becomes dead simple - just provide and resolve

This keeps the flexibility of the original design while making the composition patterns more explicit and self-contained. It also makes it easier to add new Sigil types - they just need to define their resolution chain.

